00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:15,320
still make good grounded things happen. How can 
you allow disconfirming evidence to show up that  

361
00:28:15,320 --> 00:28:20,080
doesn't kill you, that helps make you stronger? 
And if it all has to come in one massive moment  

362
00:28:20,080 --> 00:28:23,560
that could ruin everything, then you aren't 
going to hear it. And then it will build up  

363
00:28:23,560 --> 00:28:27,680
and build up and build up and build up into 
a super critical state that could shatter.

364
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:31,680
I was just listening to a couple podcasts, and a 
thread that came up in a number of them is some  

365
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:37,320
of the most successful leaders, their instruction 
to their reports is, "As soon as there's bad news,  

366
00:28:37,320 --> 00:28:40,520
I need to know as soon as possible. Do 
not shield me. I just want to know all  

367
00:28:40,520 --> 00:28:44,760
the bad news as soon as possible." Feels like 
that's one solution to what you're describing.

368
00:28:44,760 --> 00:28:51,480
Disconfirming evidence hurts, and so you won't 
realize it because it hurts at any given moment.  

369
00:28:51,480 --> 00:28:54,480
It's like, "Ugh, it's a distraction. We're 
just trying to get this thing done." And so  

370
00:28:54,480 --> 00:28:57,440
it comes from a good place to not get it, but if 
you're busy, that's one of the reason you need  

371
00:28:57,440 --> 00:29:00,840
to take a step back. We take a step back, 
you're a little bit calmer. You can absorb  

372
00:29:00,840 --> 00:29:04,560
this as confirming evidence. It doesn't feel 
like an existential threat. It's really easy  

373
00:29:04,560 --> 00:29:08,560
to get surrounded. If you are very powerful, 
you will find all the confirming evidence  

374
00:29:08,560 --> 00:29:12,880
you need. And if it doesn't exist, it will 
be created for you without your knowledge. 

375
00:29:12,880 --> 00:29:17,800
And so this is one of the reasons that large 
companies are radically different than smaller  

376
00:29:17,800 --> 00:29:23,440
companies. And one of the traps that you can get 
into of not realizing this dynamic is happening,  

377
00:29:23,440 --> 00:29:27,320
and you can make very bad decisions if you 
don't understand that it's inherently what's  

378
00:29:27,320 --> 00:29:30,880
happening because they're all, "Oh, we'll have 
some bad actors." No, no, no. If people don't  

379
00:29:30,880 --> 00:29:35,320
play this game, this game is emergent. It shows 
up even though everybody hates it. And if you  

380
00:29:35,320 --> 00:29:39,600
don't play the game, you are knocked out of the 
game. The underlying dynamic that must be true  

381
00:29:39,600 --> 00:29:45,680
in any organization on a fundamental basis is you 
can't make your boss look dumb because if you do,  

382
00:29:45,680 --> 00:29:50,680
they're the person who decides, "Oh, this person's 
not performing," or whatever. And that one little  

383
00:29:50,680 --> 00:29:55,240
asymmetry, that one little fact, in most cases 
it does not matter. That one little asymmetry is  

384
00:29:55,240 --> 00:29:59,600
what leads to the systemic compounding thing where 
you get these really weird dysfunctional emergent  

385
00:29:59,600 --> 00:30:05,760
things that everybody hates, nobody wants, and 
yet nobody is in the position to change per se.

386
00:30:05,760 --> 00:30:08,560
I love your caveat at the beginning 
that continues to resonate in my head  

387
00:30:08,560 --> 00:30:12,200
as you say this. You're not cynical 
about, "This sucks." It's more,  

388
00:30:12,200 --> 00:30:16,280
"Here's what I'm observing. We need to 
think about ways to get around this."

389
00:30:16,280 --> 00:30:22,280
Yeah. Because I think so much pain and misery 
is caused by us being not acknowledging these  

390
00:30:22,280 --> 00:30:27,320
fundamental, inescapable things. It's almost 
impossible. Entropy is one of those things.  

391
00:30:27,320 --> 00:30:31,040
Entropy emerges because there's more ways to 
go away from a point than towards a point. It  

392
00:30:31,040 --> 00:30:36,000
fundamentally must be true in really any universe 
you can possibly imagine. And so if you're going  

393
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:40,360
to fight entropy, you're going to lose at a 
certain point. It's like if you are aware of these  

394
00:30:40,360 --> 00:30:46,560
things, you can find subsets of ideas that do work 
despite these challenges. And that's some of the  

395
00:30:46,560 --> 00:30:52,160
stuff, the tactics I advise are often things that 
look playful. They look unserious. They look like,  

396
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:55,200
"Oh, you're saying you don't know the answer?" 
No, I'm admitting I don't know the answer. 

397
00:30:55,200 --> 00:30:58,760
And I'm saying it doesn't matter if I don't 
know the answer because this thing, this  

398
00:30:58,760 --> 00:31:03,880
very small seed I am planting is so cheap that 
yes, I can't tell you for sure this will work,  

399
00:31:03,880 --> 00:31:07,440
but I could tell you there is a chance that it'll 
work. And the downside of this is basically the  

400
00:31:07,440 --> 00:31:12,040
opportunity cost of planting the seed in this one 
moment, and the person who's planting it enjoys  

401
00:31:12,040 --> 00:31:15,240
planting it so that an opportunity cost really 
isn't that much because they get energy from  

402
00:31:15,240 --> 00:31:20,640
doing it. So who cares? Plant a bunch of these 
suckers. If one of these grows into an oak tree,  

403
00:31:20,640 --> 00:31:24,200
that's great. Don't try to analyze beforehand 
which seed is going to turn into an oak tree.  

404
00:31:24,200 --> 00:31:28,360
If it's super simple to plant the seeds, then 
plant the seeds. And if it starts growing, then  

405
00:31:28,360 --> 00:31:32,680
keep watering it. That's it. That's the thing.
And people sometimes will see this as like,  

406
00:31:32,680 --> 00:31:35,640
I've been called in my list before because they 
said, "Well, you're saying that you don't know  

407
00:31:35,640 --> 00:31:39,400
the answer to the thing." It's like no, I'm saying 
I don't have to know the answer to the thing. If  

408
00:31:39,400 --> 00:31:43,800
on a systemic basis I let these ideas and then 
you respond to the ones that are working that  

409
00:31:43,800 --> 00:31:48,400
are viable, it doesn't really matter if you didn't 
know ahead of time which ones were going to work.

410
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:53,400
It's a great segue to talking about this core 
idea that again informs a lot of the way you  

411
00:31:53,400 --> 00:31:58,280
think, which is this idea of building 
versus gardening, the magic of acorns.  

412
00:31:58,280 --> 00:32:02,240
Talk about this general idea and 
then I want to follow some threads.

413
00:32:02,240 --> 00:32:07,120
So much of the way that we tackle problems and 
build products is this builder mindset. It's like,  

414
00:32:07,120 --> 00:32:12,320
"I have a plan, I then manipulate things to match 
my plan and make it happen." And this is a way  

415
00:32:12,320 --> 00:32:16,160
you can create tons of value. Part of the problem 
though is it can't possibly create more value than  

416
00:32:16,160 --> 00:32:19,840
the effort that you put into it. And so what I 
look for instead are things that can be gardened,  

417
00:32:19,840 --> 00:32:24,480
things that can grow on their own and that you 
can direct or maybe give a little bit of extra  

418
00:32:24,480 --> 00:32:30,640
energy to or curate over, and is a totally 
different mindset for it. So it's like a  

419
00:32:30,640 --> 00:32:35,880
lead by gardening vibe. I don't try to pick 
the things in the system. I try to work with  

420
00:32:35,880 --> 00:32:39,960
what I've actually got and I try to lean in 
on the ones that turn, I think are going in  

421
00:32:39,960 --> 00:32:44,760
the direction that I believe is valuable based 
on constantly seeking disconfirming evidence. 

422
00:32:44,760 --> 00:32:51,400
And if you do this properly, it looks like magic. 
It looks like a thing. It looks like getting lucky  

423
00:32:51,400 --> 00:32:56,400
because what you're doing is you're farming for 
miracles. And so on a systemic basis, I can't tell  

424
00:32:56,400 --> 00:33:00,040
you which of these things will work, but I can 
tell you there's a very high likelihood that one  

425
00:33:00,040 --> 00:33:04,760
of these will work in a way that is interesting 
and transformative. And so if you're looking and  

426
00:33:04,760 --> 00:33:08,440
finding these seeds that have the compounding 
potential of if they work, they would start  

427
00:33:08,440 --> 00:33:14,600
working at an accelerating rate, then you don't 
have to know ahead of time. To me this is, I've  

428
00:33:14,600 --> 00:33:20,720
been told that this is completely against all the 
advice that people get building products nowadays,  

429
00:33:21,880 --> 00:33:26,680
but I think it's a very powerful approach 
that works in a lot of different contexts.

430
00:33:26,680 --> 00:33:31,520
Is there an example that you can give from either 
from something you worked on or something someone  

431
00:33:31,520 --> 00:33:35,200
worked on that came or true miss? Because 
I think people hearing this might be like,  

432
00:33:35,200 --> 00:33:38,280
"But I got to ship stuff. I got to 
hit some goals. I don't have time  

433
00:33:38,280 --> 00:33:41,920
to sit around and garden and plant 
seeds. I got to actually build."

434
00:33:41,920 --> 00:33:46,080
If there's an ecosystem approach, if 
there's something that if it works,  

435
00:33:46,080 --> 00:33:49,200
it'll be self-accelerating. So okay, what 
you're going to do this thing, we aren't  

436
00:33:49,200 --> 00:33:53,080
entirely sure what's going to work, but if a 
developer writes a thing and somebody uses it,  

437
00:33:53,080 --> 00:33:57,520
it'll attract more developers, more users, 
and then this would grow on its own. Then  

438
00:33:57,520 --> 00:34:01,840
and it's cheap to do the little example of the 
thing. It's cheap to build a little open source,  

439
00:34:01,840 --> 00:34:05,920
tinker the little thing and just put it there. And 
if nobody uses it, it's fine. It was fun to build.  

440
00:34:05,920 --> 00:34:09,800
It took you three hours. It's fine. If someone 
does use it, then you just invest in incremental  

441
00:34:09,800 --> 00:34:13,840
bit of unit each time that you find a signal that 
somebody is finding it useful and then you stop  

442
00:34:13,840 --> 00:34:18,560
if you ever cease getting that information.
So I would use this. Anything that is shaped  

443
00:34:18,560 --> 00:34:22,600
like an ecosystem that has some kind of network 
effect, and many things have network effects,  

444
00:34:22,600 --> 00:34:27,207
have some kind of compounding loop. Compounding 
loops are not rare. They are, "Look." It's  

445
00:34:28,040 --> 00:34:32,160
like truffle hunting. You have to know what you're 
looking for and find the dynamics of a thing that  

446
00:34:32,160 --> 00:34:36,520
if it worked would work at an accelerating rate. 
Lots and lots and lots of things intrinsically  

447
00:34:36,520 --> 00:34:41,040
have this shape. Anything with a network effect, 
anything where the power goes up with a number  

448
00:34:41,040 --> 00:34:47,080
of users, but it shows up in all kinds of 
problems that we don't normally apply it to.

449
00:34:47,080 --> 00:34:54,600
Along the same lines, you also advise people to 
think more emergence-oriented versus top-down,  

450
00:34:54,600 --> 00:34:57,040
kind of what you were just saying. But I 
think that's another really interesting  

451
00:34:57,040 --> 00:35:00,480
way of thinking about the same idea, 
create opportunities for emergence,  

452
00:35:00,480 --> 00:35:03,520
bottom-up versus top-down 
control. You just chat about that.

453
00:35:03,520 --> 00:35:07,400
100%. I think the emergence is one of the most 
powerful forces if you know how to marshal  

454
00:35:07,400 --> 00:35:11,400
it and you know how to work with it. And the 
only thing that's hard about it in my opinion  

455
00:35:11,400 --> 00:35:15,160
is you're going to look like you aren't very 
serious. You're going to look like a weirdo.  

456
00:35:15,160 --> 00:35:20,200
You're going to look like a cook. And one of 
the downsides, if you're working on something  

457
00:35:20,200 --> 00:35:23,880
and you're doing the normal top-down approach 
where you make the plan, you execute the plan,  

458
00:35:23,880 --> 00:35:28,000
even if the plan turns out to not be useful, you 
produce a thing and nothing interesting happens,  

459
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:32,120
no one can say you didn't work hard. 
But if you try doing this designing for  

460
00:35:32,120 --> 00:35:35,080
emergence and something amazing happens, 
even once it happens, people go, "Ah,  

461
00:35:35,080 --> 00:35:40,360
it's luck. Where was the miraculous moment, 
the heroic moment where you made that happen?  

462
00:35:40,360 --> 00:35:45,280
So therefore you had nothing to do with it."
And this was the biggest unlock in my career  

463
00:35:45,280 --> 00:35:48,480
actually was when I stopped my guts. I was 
promoted to director at Google. I was like,  

464
00:35:48,480 --> 00:35:53,880
"Cool, I never want to be promoted inside of a 
large organization ever again." And the freedom  

465
00:35:53,880 --> 00:35:59,200
to now do the highest impact work, even if 
I can't make it legible to the organization,  

466
00:35:59,200 --> 00:36:03,960
was so powerful and I was able to 10X my impact 
for the organization because I didn't have to  

467
00:36:03,960 --> 00:36:09,160
worry about making it measurable specifically in 
a way that would show individual work effort. And  

468
00:36:09,160 --> 00:36:13,440
I think that's the hardest part. And you have 
to have, typically what I would advise for PMs,  

469
00:36:13,440 --> 00:36:18,640
my approach at Google was 70% of my effort 
and my team's effort should go on things that  

470
00:36:18,640 --> 00:36:24,160
everybody acknowledges are important and useful 
and create value. Maybe it's boring, linear value,  

471
00:36:24,160 --> 00:36:28,480
but some kind of value. You're trying to minimize 
the chance that any other person in a company  

472
00:36:28,480 --> 00:36:33,600
will say, "What does that team do anyway?"
This, if someone says this about your team,  

473
00:36:33,600 --> 00:36:37,240
your team is on the verge of death. And so you're 
trying to minimize the chance that anybody wants  

474
00:36:37,240 --> 00:36:41,080
to say that or thinks that it's appropriate to 
say that by clearly and unambiguously adding  

475
00:36:41,080 --> 00:36:44,680
value. You're not saying this is the best team 
in the entire world, but clearly they're doing  

476
00:36:44,680 --> 00:36:48,320
something useful. They're executing well. They're 
working hard. And of course that team should  

477
00:36:48,320 --> 00:36:52,760
exist. Think about it, of course they should. 
But now once you do this, you have 30% of your  

478
00:36:52,760 --> 00:36:57,080
extra time that you can plant all these seeds.
You can find interesting little things where  

479
00:36:57,080 --> 00:37:01,280
maybe a junior PM on the team has an idea you 
think it's kind of silly, but they're really into  

480
00:37:01,280 --> 00:37:04,880
it. And the there is this thing, it could work 
out great actually. If you tweak it like this,  

481
00:37:04,880 --> 00:37:09,000
there is a potential. I could see how that could 
work. If that PM is going to work on that anyway,  

482
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:12,320
they want to do it anyway. Instead of saying, 
"No, no, no, we don't have time for that. Be  

483
00:37:12,320 --> 00:37:16,640
a little bit more productive over here," say, 
"Go for it. Here's my concerns. I imagine this  

484
00:37:16,640 --> 00:37:21,200
part might not work, but this part is really 
cool right here." And then if it doesn't work,  

485
00:37:21,200 --> 00:37:25,600
then they've stretched their agency. They've 
executed. They've exercised their agency. They've  

486
00:37:25,600 --> 00:37:30,760
learned. They've gotten stronger. They've grown. 
It has the upside if it turns out to actually  

487
00:37:30,760 --> 00:37:35,560
work. And worst case scenario, the opportunity 
cost to doing the thing that helped them grow  

488
00:37:35,560 --> 00:37:40,040
and they learn and they liked. So I don't know. 
Don't try to force it. Don't try to stop it.

489
00:37:40,040 --> 00:37:43,360
That's a really good example of actually 
how to go about doing that on your team.  

490
00:37:43,360 --> 00:37:47,080
The way I've always thought about this is 
the visual I share with people is like,  

