don't do big things." But when you recognize 
that your adjacent possible is relatively small,  

898
01:08:57,760 --> 01:09:02,840
you realize that you actually have full agency to 
pick within the subset that is within your reach,  

899
01:09:02,840 --> 01:09:06,920
and your actions matter because you take 
an action and now the world reconfigures  

900
01:09:06,920 --> 01:09:11,840
and now you get a next set of actions and it's 
based partially on the action you just took. 

901
01:09:11,840 --> 01:09:16,240
And so if you slice this thing up and you have 
a coherent worldview and you have a principled  

902
01:09:16,240 --> 01:09:20,640
approach, you can arc to wildly different 
outcomes than look like they were possible  

903
01:09:20,640 --> 01:09:25,920
while at each point, each individual action 
is safe and reasonable. And so you can combine  

904
01:09:25,920 --> 01:09:30,480
both of these things. I think so many times 
we try to jump and we jump to the end state  

905
01:09:30,480 --> 01:09:34,400
of the thing. And actually you don't need to 
make that decision. If you can slice up your  

906
01:09:34,400 --> 01:09:38,400
decisions into smaller and smaller decisions, I'm 
like, "This next step definitely makes sense."  

907
01:09:38,400 --> 01:09:41,680
It will almost certainly pay for itself or the 
very least won't be too expensive. And then it  

908
01:09:41,680 --> 01:09:45,000
might allow these other things to happen and you 
take it. And if those other things don't happen,  

909
01:09:45,000 --> 01:09:47,840
okay, don't take another step on that 
path. That's fine. Go in other directions  

910
01:09:47,840 --> 01:09:51,280
for a while. If it does, then take another 
step and another and another and another. 

911
01:09:51,280 --> 01:09:56,040
And this allows you to get rid of a lot of the 
risk and still be exposed to all the upside.  

912
01:09:56,040 --> 01:10:02,440
And so the risk comes from trying to jump 
too far ahead in an unknown environment.

913
01:10:02,440 --> 01:10:05,560
Is the general advice if someone's working 
on trying to figure out the roadmap,  

914
01:10:05,560 --> 01:10:09,040
trying to think about what products to 
build is the advice, don't be scared  

915
01:10:09,040 --> 01:10:13,840
to go a little incremental versus what 
people are always pushed, to do bigger.

916
01:10:13,840 --> 01:10:19,840
You need both. So if you only do incremental, you 
will follow the shortest, the steepest gradient  

917
01:10:19,840 --> 01:10:23,720
in front of you. So UXR says a user wants to do 
this and you'll do exactly that and you'll end  

918
01:10:23,720 --> 01:10:27,240
up random walking through the thing. So you need 
coherence about where you're going and the way you  

919
01:10:27,240 --> 01:10:31,880
get that is by creating a North Star for yourself. 
It should be in three to five years in the future,  

920
01:10:31,880 --> 01:10:35,680
it should be very low resolution. It should 
describe a thing that every single person who  

921
01:10:35,680 --> 01:10:40,800
reads it who has any kind of knowledge that might 
be useful or relevant agrees that it is plausible.  

922
01:10:40,800 --> 01:10:43,880
If this happens, I would not say, "Well, a 
miracle happened." It'd say, "I could see how  

923
01:10:43,880 --> 01:10:46,960
that could work." And lawyers say, "I could see 
how that could work." And someone who's worked  

924
01:10:46,960 --> 01:10:51,320
on this 30 years ago at a similar product that 
Microsoft says, "I can see how that could work." 

925
01:10:51,320 --> 01:10:54,720
And that if you got to the end point, everyone 
would high five because if it's going to be a  

926
01:10:54,720 --> 01:10:58,600
thing, they're like, "I guess that could work." At 
the end we'd be like, "Oh yeah, neat." That's not  

927
01:10:58,600 --> 01:11:03,640
worth it. You want another story would be like, 
"Yeah, great. Wow, we kick off. We changed the way  

928
01:11:03,640 --> 01:11:07,720
this entire industry works," or whatever. And now 
this is your North Star. North Star should update,  

929
01:11:07,720 --> 01:11:11,800
but it's because it's far off in the distance. 
It will update. It will slide up across the sky  

930
01:11:11,800 --> 01:11:18,040
a little bit. It won't be jerking around. You'll 
be arcing slightly differently. And then what you  

931
01:11:18,040 --> 01:11:21,280
do is you look in your adjacent possible and 
you look for the thing that has the steepest  

932
01:11:21,280 --> 01:11:25,040
gradient that pulls you towards your North Star. 
So you just want to go in that direction and you  

933
01:11:25,040 --> 01:11:28,920
want to go in this direction. This one is 
second most in demand from what you think,  

934
01:11:28,920 --> 01:11:31,640
but it's pulling you the direction that you 
believe will pull you there. Go in that one. 

935
01:11:31,640 --> 01:11:36,320
And then they keep on repeating. That's it. But 
you need both. Because if you only do incremental,  

936
01:11:36,320 --> 01:11:39,760
then you'll end up random walking into a 
corner. And if you only do the long-term,  

937
01:11:39,760 --> 01:11:45,800
you end up dreaming big and designing castles in 
the sky that are impossible to actually manifest.

938
01:11:45,800 --> 01:11:49,400
To give you a metaphor from an experience I 
had, I did this silent meditation retreat once,  

939
01:11:49,400 --> 01:11:54,520
and a big part of Buddhism is to not cling 
to a specific outcome and not have a plan  

940
01:11:54,520 --> 01:11:59,200
in mind and be sad if it doesn't work out. 
And so I asked them just how do you achieve  

941
01:11:59,200 --> 01:12:06,000
success and want to be successful while not 
doing that? And their metaphor is point your  

942
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:11,240
card in a specific direction that you want to 
go. Just point your card in that direction,  

943
01:12:11,240 --> 01:12:16,320
essentially in your example of North Star, 
and just start walking. Don't figure out  

944
01:12:16,320 --> 01:12:19,440
this is exactly the path I'm going to 
take to get to this end destination.

945
01:12:19,440 --> 01:12:24,520
Yeah. And you'll know after the fact, you'll say, 
"Oh, I curved a little bit or I had this little  

946
01:12:24,520 --> 01:12:28,560
jog than there." And you'll say, "Ah, it would've 
been more efficient." But we're so focused on  

947
01:12:28,560 --> 01:12:32,320
efficiency of not wasting effort that we ended 
up doing nothing at all or doing very dangerous  

948
01:12:32,320 --> 01:12:35,680
things that don't work. So I'm much sure that I 
have a path that's slightly inefficient because  

949
01:12:35,680 --> 01:12:38,880
we're navigating unknowns and we couldn't know 
no point. I think I've seen the number of times I  

950
01:12:38,880 --> 01:12:44,920
find where people say, "I need to know for this 
strategy," that someone was trying to get me  

951
01:12:44,920 --> 01:12:53,000
to look at and then say, "is this number in five 
years, is it going to be 93 or 95?" And it's like,  

952
01:12:53,000 --> 01:12:56,880
I don't know. And it doesn't matter either 
if it's going to be that order of magnitude. 

953
01:12:56,880 --> 01:13:00,800
It doesn't matter, and we don't have to do that 
analysis if we believe that the order of magnitude  

954
01:13:00,800 --> 01:13:05,400
is of that thing. It'd actually be we had spent 
all the time to get the illusion of precision,  

955
01:13:05,400 --> 01:13:09,360
which at great expense, and then it's the 
people say, "Oh, I'm data-driven. I want to  

956
01:13:09,360 --> 01:13:12,720
really run the analysis to ground." There's 
tons of stuff you can't know ahead of time.  

957
01:13:12,720 --> 01:13:17,320
So if you're getting a false precision at the 
beginner, that's a comfort blanket. That's just  

958
01:13:17,320 --> 01:13:22,720
helping you feel like there isn't uncertainty. 
There's uncertainty everywhere all the time. And  

959
01:13:22,720 --> 01:13:26,640
trying to ignore it by trying to pin it down 
with fake numbers that you just made up for  

960
01:13:26,640 --> 01:13:32,520
yourself at great expense is a really bad idea. 
And that's why if the ideas are strong enough,  

961
01:13:32,520 --> 01:13:37,080
things that have a compounding return don't give 
you, "Oh, we'll either get 93 or 95." It's like,  

962
01:13:37,080 --> 01:13:43,440
"We'll either get zero or we'll get 1,000." Great. 
It doesn't really matter if it's 1,000 or 1,001,  

963
01:13:43,440 --> 01:13:48,680
who cares? It orders a magnitude larger 
than the alternative, and so it is better.

